SIMPLE: scorn
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scorn
<hw>Scorn</hw> <pr>(sk⟦ocir⟧rn)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>scorn</ets>, <ets>scarn</ets>, <ets>scharn</ets>, OF.
<ets>escarn</ets>, <ets>escharn</ets>, <ets>eschar</ets>, of German
origin; cf. OHG. <ets>skern</ets> mockery, <ets>skern⟦omac⟧n</ets> to
mock; but cf. also OF. <ets>escorner</ets> to mock.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Extreme and lofty contempt; haughty disregard; that disdain which
springs from the opinion of the utter meanness and unworthiness of an
object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Scorn</qex> at first makes after love the more.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And wandered backward as in <qex>scorn</qex>,⟦br⟧
To wait an aeon to be born.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An act or expression of extreme contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every sullen frown and bitter <qex>scorn</qex>⟦br⟧
But fanned the fuel that too fast did burn.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An object of extreme disdain, contempt, or
derision.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou makest us a reproach to our neighbors, a <qex>scorn</qex> and
a derision to them that are round about us.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xliv.
13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To think scorn</b></col>, <cd>to regard as worthy of
scorn or contempt; to disdain.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧He <xex>thought scorn</xex>
to lay hands on Mordecai alone.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Esther iii. 6.</au> --
<col><b>To laugh to scorn</b></col>, <cd>to deride; to make a mock of;
to ridicule as contemptible.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Contempt; disdain; derision; contumely; despite;
slight; dishonor; mockery.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scorn</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scorn
<hw>Scorn</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scorned</conjf> <pr>(sk⟦ocir⟧rnd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Scoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>scornen</ets>,
<ets>scarnen</ets>, <ets>schornen</ets>, OF. <ets>escarnir</ets>,
<ets>escharnir</ets>. See <er>Scorn</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To hold in extreme contempt; to reject as unworthy of
regard; to despise; to contemn; to disdain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>scorn</qex> thy meat; 't would choke me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This my long sufferance, and my day of grace,⟦br⟧
Those who neglect and <qex>scorn</qex> shall never taste.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>scorn</qex> what is in itself contemptible or
disgraceful.</q> <rj><qau>C. J. Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To treat with extreme contempt; to make the object
of insult; to mock; to scoff at; to deride.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His fellow, that lay by his bed's side,⟦br⟧
Gan for to laugh, and <qex>scorned</qex> him full fast.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To taunt and <qex>scorn</qex> you thus opprobriously.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To contemn; despise; disdain. See
<er>Contemn</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1290 pr=PCP --></p>

<p><ent>Scorn</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scorn
<hw>Scorn</hw> <pr>(sk⟦ocir⟧rn)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To scoff; to
mock; to show contumely, derision, or reproach; to act
disdainfully.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He said mine eyes were black and my hair black,⟦br⟧
And, now I am remembered, <qex>scorned</qex> at me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scorner</ent>⟦br⟧
